ing-while-giving places women at the heart of the political process, however much that process may vary in different societies, for women possess a wealth of their own that gives them power. Power is intimately involved in cultural reproduction, and Weiner describes the location of power in each society, showing how the degree of control over the production and distribution of cloth wealth coincides with women's rank and the development of hierarchy in the community. Other inalienable possessions, whether material objects, landed property, ancestral myths, or sacred knowledge, bestow social identity and rank as well. Calling attention to their presence in Western history, Weiner points out that her formulations are not limited to Oceania. The paradox of keeping-while-giving is a concept certain to influence future developments in ethnography and the theoretical study of gender and exchange.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAnthropologie économiquexMéthodologiexOcéaniexOzeanienxOceania. 0aCeremonial exchangexOceania. 0aCeremonial exchangezOceania. 0aEconomic anthropologyxMethodologyxOceania. 0aEconomic anthropologyzOceaniaxMethodology. 0aFeminist anthropologyxOceania. 0aFeminist anthropologyzOceania. 0aFemmesxConditions socialesxOcéanie. 0aFemmesxConditions économiquesxOcéanie. 0aWomenxEconomic conditionsxOceania. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxOceania. 0aWomenzOceaniaxEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzOceaniaxSocial conditions. 0aÉchange cérémonielxOcéanie. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520911802.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  Universi